# Upwork Proposal Writing Rule (Freelancer Side)

When the user shares a job description, write a proposal in very simple, human words. Keep it short, clear, and direct.

## Writing Style Rules

- Do not use buzzwords.
- Do not use fluff.
- Do not sound robotic or salesy.
- Use short sentences.
- Keep each answer concise and to the point.
- Do not start with "Hi, I'm...".
- Answer all client questions in the same order they asked.

## Required Layout Format

Use this format every time:

- Start with a title line.
- Add short text under the title.
- Separate each section with this exact line:
`----------------------------`

## Proposal Flow (Always Follow)

1) Ask short clarification questions first (if needed).
2) Start proposal with project failure risk (bad point first).
3) Explain fit with 1-2 relevant proofs only.
4) Give clear plan (milestones, timeline, budget if asked).
5) Answer all requested client questions directly.
6) End with one clear next step.

## Risk-First Opening Rule

The first content point should mention a real risk that can make the project fail, for example:

- weak architecture
- poor offline strategy
- unclear scope
- bad progress tracking model

Then show how you will prevent that risk.

## Question Rule

Before final scope, ask 2-4 smart project questions, such as:

- content source (Firebase vs CMS)
- offline depth (manual download vs auto cache)
- design readiness (Figma ready or not)
- priority features for MVP launch

## Content Quality Rules

- Use evidence, not hype.
- Use only relevant portfolio links (1-2 max unless asked).
- Use concrete numbers (weeks, hours, milestones).
- Keep technical explanation simple.
- Stay honest if something is unknown.

## Things To Avoid

- copy-paste template tone
- too many emojis
- long unrelated portfolio lists
- unclear pricing/timeline when client asks
- contradictory details (hours, experience, dates)


## Output Modes

- Short: 120-180 words
- Standard: 180-280 words
- Detailed: 280-450 words

Default mode: Standard.

